<script lang="ts">
	import MaterialsList from './components/MaterialsList.svelte';
	import Introduction from './components/Introduction.svelte';
	import DiscussionPrompts from './components/DiscussionPrompts.svelte';
	import ReflectionQuestions from './components/ReflectionQuestions.svelte';
	import AssessmentCriteria from './components/AssessmentCriteria.svelte';
	import CustomSection from './components/CustomSection.svelte';
	import { getSdgColor } from '$lib/utils/sdg-colors';

	interface Props {
		sdgColor?: string;
	}

	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(10) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Spacious and safe dance studio or open classroom","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or projector","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers, pens","isOptional":false},{"name":"Music players equal to the amount of dance groups, so each can rehearse with their chosen music","isOptional":false},{"name":"Notebooks or paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/Pencils","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Dancing for Equality: Exploring the Legacy of Alvin Ailey & Modern Dance"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin by showing a short video clip(s) of Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater performing an excerpt from an iconic piece.<br>Examples<br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TqcHHF0c_EU\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“Revelations”</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5UH82JHoSA\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“Blues Suite”</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=csi1sLsEcug\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“Cry”</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R15F52EWnDU\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“Survivors”</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-w_77mXcNCA\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Streams</em></a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jVf7fMAh12I\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Reflections in D</em></a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k5IoS5gSA74\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Wade in the Water</em></a><br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What do you notice about the dancers’ movements and expressions?<br></em> How does the music make you feel?<br><em> What messages or stories do you think the dancers are trying to convey?<br>Facilitate a discussion about Alvin Ailey’s life and legacy.<br>Key Points<br></em> Born in Texas in 1931, experienced racial segregation and discrimination.<br><em> Founded the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater in 1958, creating a multiracial company that celebrated African American culture and heritage.<br></em> His choreography is known for its powerful storytelling, emotional depth, and social relevance.<br><em> “Revelations” (1960) is his most famous work, exploring themes of faith, hope, and resilience in the face of adversity.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> Why do you think Ailey’s work was so groundbreaking and impactful?<br><em> How can dance be used to express social and political messages?<br></em> How does Ailey’s background and experiences inform his choreography?<br>Introduce/re-introduce Global Goal 10: Reduced Inequalities. Explain the core idea of reducing inequality within and among countries, ensuring equal opportunities for and access to resources for all.<br>Briefly introduce all the different targets within Global Goal 10, highlighting their interconnectedness and importance.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some of the causes and consequences of inequality?<br></em> How does inequality affect different people and communities around the world?\n<ul>\n<li>What can we do to create a more just and equitable world?</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exploring Ailey’s Movement Style"} content={"<p>Begin with a gentle warm-up to prepare students’ bodies for movement.<br>Play upbeat and rhythmic music to energize students and get them moving during the warm-up. This can include a variety of music selections, including spirituals, gospel, blues, and jazz, reflecting the diverse influences in Ailey’s choreography.<br>Examples<br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VaPCXRNFzUI\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wade in the Water</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=adi_RESrcyQ&amp;list=PLJa-XdbM-QRCVfy4TSovIxykw9uLAbZMY&amp;index=11\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sinner Man</a><br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VaPCXRNFzUI&amp;list=PLJa-XdbM-QRCVfy4TSovIxykw9uLAbZMY\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Revelations</a> (by Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater)<br>Include stretches, basic exercises, and simple movement sequences.<br>Introduce basic modern dance techniques inspired by Ailey’s style.<br><em>Contraction and Release:</em> Explore the concept of contracting and releasing the torso, a key element in Ailey’s choreography.<br><em>Fall and Recovery:</em> Practice falling and recovering from the floor, emphasizing fluidity and control.<br><em>Flexibility and Extension:</em> Encourage students to explore their flexibility and range of motion through stretches and extensions.<br><em>Grounded Movement:</em> Emphasize the importance of connecting with the floor and using gravity to create powerful and expressive movements.<br>Introduce a basic movement vocabulary inspired by Ailey’s choreography.<br>Examples<br><em> Strong, grounded movements representing resilience and determination (connection to Target 10.1 \\- income growth).<br></em> Contracting movements representing oppression or struggle (connection to Target 10.2 \\- social inclusion).<br><em> Reaching movements symbolizing hope and aspiration (connection to Target 10.3 \\- equal opportunity).<br></em> Have students share their own movement vocabulary and how it connects to different targets in Global Goal 10\\.<br>Combine the basic techniques and movement vocabulary to create short movement phrases. Demonstrate the phrases and have students practice them, encouraging them to explore their own interpretations and expressions.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Dance and Global Goal 10"} content={"<p>Facilitate a brainstorming session where students generate ideas for dance pieces that connect to different targets within Global Goal 10, or to the Goal holistically.<br>Encourage students to consider how music can enhance their expression of the chosen target/Global Goal 10\\.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some movement qualities or dynamics that could represent each target?<br></em> How can we use dance to convey the challenges and opportunities associated with each target?<br><em> How can we use dance to express the interconnectedness of the different targets within Global Goal 10?<br>Examples<br></em> <strong>Target 10.1</strong> <em>(Income Growth):</em> Create a dance piece with upward reaching movements and dynamic changes in levels, representing the growth and progress of individuals and communities overcoming poverty.<br><em> <strong>Target 10.2</strong> </em>(Social Inclusion):<em> Create a dance with movements that connect and intertwine, symbolizing the inclusion and integration of diverse individuals and groups in society.<br></em> <strong>Target 10.3</strong> <em>(Equal Opportunity):</em> Choreograph a dance with movements that break free from restrictions and limitations, representing the struggle for equality and the dismantling of discriminatory barriers.<br><em> <strong>Target 10.4</strong> </em>(Social Protection):<em> Create a dance piece with supportive and nurturing movements, representing the safety net and support systems that protect vulnerable populations.<br></em> <strong>Target 10.5</strong> <em>(Financial Markets):</em> Develop a dance with intricate and interconnected movements, representing the complexity of financial systems and the need for regulation and transparency.<br><em> <strong>Target 10.6</strong> </em>(Global Institutions):<em> Choreograph a dance with a group of dancers moving in unison and with individual expression, representing the importance of global cooperation and diverse voices in decision-making.<br></em> <strong>Target 10.7</strong> <em>(Migration):</em> Create a dance piece with fluid and journeying movements, representing the experiences of migrants and the challenges and opportunities they face.<br><em> <strong>Target 10.a</strong> </em>(Special and Differential Treatment):<em> Develop a dance with contrasting movements representing the imbalance of power between developed and developing countries, advocating for fair treatment and support for developing nations.<br></em> <strong>Target 10.b</strong> <em>(Development Assistance):</em> Choreograph a dance with movements of giving and receiving, representing the importance of international cooperation and assistance in reducing inequalities.<br><em> <strong>Target 10.c</strong> </em>(Remittances):* Create a dance piece with movements that connect and bridge distances, representing the flow of remittances and their impact on families and communities.<br>Divide students into groups, the size of your choosing.<br>Each group selects one target from Global Goal 10 (or can focus on the Goal holistically) and creates a short dance piece (2-3 minutes) inspired by Ailey’s style and incorporating the movement vocabulary learned earlier.<br>Encourage students to be creative and expressive in their choreography, using movement to convey the essence of their chosen target.<br>Guide students to select music that complements their choreography and effectively conveys the message of their chosen target/Global Goal 10\\.<br>Encourage them to explore a range of musical styles and consider how the music can enhance the emotional impact of their dance. If students are struggling to find appropriate music, provide suggestions or curate a playlist of diverse music options for them to choose from.<br>Provide time for students to rehearse and refine their dance pieces.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<DiscussionPrompts prompts={["What were some of the most powerful or memorable dance pieces or movements you saw?","How did these pieces make you think differently about Global Goal 10?","What were some of the common themes or messages you noticed in the dances?","How did the use of movement and Ailey’s style enhance the expression of ideas and emotions?"]} {sdgColor} />

	<ReflectionQuestions questions={["How did exploring Alvin Ailey’s dance style and embodying themes of justice and resilience through movement deepen your understanding of Global Goal 10?","What emotions or messages did you feel were most powerfully communicated through the movement in your own piece, or in the pieces you observed?","Did the act of physically expressing concepts like struggle, hope, or empowerment connect you to the issue of inequality in a different way than just discussing it?","What did you learn about strength and dignity of individuals facing inequality through the movement explorations inspired by Ailey’s legacy?","How can dance, as a universal language, help bridge understanding and empathy across different experiences of inequality?","How did learning about Alvin Ailey’s life and the inspiration behind his work, particularly “Revelations” or “Cry,” illuminate the role of dance as a tool for social justice?","What specific elements of Ailey’s choreography (e.g., contraction/release, groundedness, expressive gestures) did you find effective in communicating themes related to Global Goal 10?","How can dance and movement be used to raise awareness and inspire action for causes like reducing inequalities, much like Ailey used his art?","How does the historical context of Ailey’s work, emerging from a time of significant social change, resonate with the contemporary challenges of Global Goal 10?","Did creating or observing the dance pieces spark any new insights about inequality in your own community or globally?","What is one key takeaway about Global Goal 10 and the importance of reducing inequalities that you will remember from this lesson?","How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in promoting a more just and equitable world?","How might you continue to use dance, movement, or other forms of creative expression to advocate for social change and equality in the future?"]} {sdgColor} />

	<AssessmentCriteria criteria={["Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the warm-up, technique explorations, group choreography, performance, and class discussions.","Comprehension of Global Goal 10, targets and core concepts. This will be evidenced through the symbolism and intention within the dance piece(s) and verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.","Originality and effectiveness in applying modern dance techniques (e.g., contraction/release, fall/recovery, groundedness) and Ailey-inspired movement qualities to convey their message about reducing inequalities.","How clearly and powerfully the finished dance piece(s) communicate the intended message about Global Goal 10\\. Did the choreography successfully evoke thought or emotion related to the goal?","Ability to work effectively within the groups, contributing ideas, respecting diverse interpretations, and working as a cohesive ensemble to create and perform the dance.","Nuance and insight demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of dance in addressing social justice issues and the complexities of achieving a more equitable world."]} {sdgColor} />

</div>
